1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
We are talking today with Colm Kelleher. He is the author of the new book Brain Trust,

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:11,000
The Hidden Connection Between Mad Cow and Misdiagnosed Alzheimer's Disease.

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:12,500
Colm, thanks for coming in today.

4
00:00:12,500 --> 00:00:14,000
Good to be here.

5
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:19,000
Start out and tell us, what was the motivation in writing your book Brain Trust?

6
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:25,000
Well, my motivation really arose from several fronts.

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:35,000
As a long-time research biochemist, I've always been interested in the underlying causes behind these mysterious brain diseases.

8
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:41,000
And the underlying cause is a very strange protein called a prion.

9
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Now, if you're looking at it from a scientific point of view, prions break all the rules, or prions as they're also called.

10
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,000
They break all of the rules. They're not like viruses, they're not like bacteria.

11
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:02,000
They're almost indestructible. They are very difficult to kill, but yet they seem to behave like infectious organisms.

12
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
So that really got my attention.

13
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:12,000
And the second thing that really got my attention was a study done from Yale University in the last few years,

14
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:20,000
and the University of Pittsburgh, in which they went into the autopsy banks of Alzheimer's disease patients,

15
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:27,000
people who had died of Alzheimer's, and they looked at their brains and they found that their brains were not,

16
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:35,000
5% or 10% of these brains were not actually Alzheimer's disease.

17
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:46,000
They had died of a totally separate disease called CJD, Christophel Jakob disease, which has ties to mad cow disease.

18
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Now, the reason that's important is because it strongly implies that the numbers of CJD cases in the United States

19
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:01,000
is dramatically underestimated by the health authorities.

20
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:09,000
Usually, if the health authorities ever talk about this, they usually talk in terms of one in a million cases, very, very rare disease.

21
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:19,000
But these studies from Yale University, University of Pittsburgh, documenting about 5% to 10% of Alzheimer's disease patients

22
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:23,000
are actually misdiagnosed and that they're really CJD.

23
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:31,000
Currently, we have between 4 and 5 million Alzheimer's patients in the United States. It is an epidemic.

24
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Alzheimer's disease has increased dramatically since the late 1970s by a factor of about 9,000%, which is an unbelievable number.

25
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:51,000
So if you look at even a tiny fraction of those Alzheimer's disease patients,

26
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:59,000
maybe even if you take a low number like 2% or 1% that are misdiagnosed and they're really CJD patients,

27
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,000
that is still an enormous number of CJD cases.

28
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:09,000
Now, the other issue that I found that motivated me to write the book is that I discovered that CJD

29
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:15,000
is not a mandatory reportable disease in the United States, in most of the states in the country.

30
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:22,000
So that's another reason for saying that the number of cases in CJD in the United States is simply not known.

31
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:28,000
And that has other implications for possibilities of numbers.

32
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:39,000
And the more numbers that are discovered for CJD, the less likely it is that these diseases arise randomly,

33
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:47,000
which is that CJD in the United States is mostly a variant called sporadic CJD,

34
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:55,000
which the CDC and the USDA, that's the Center for Disease Control and the United States Department of Agriculture,

35
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:02,000
routinely dismiss as having nothing to do with eating tainted beef.

36
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:11,000
Well, there's evidence that's coming out in the scientific literature, which has been buried really in obscure journals,

37
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:17,000
rarely sees the light of day in the media, which are definitely questioning that premise.

38
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:24,000
In other words, they're questioning the idea that mad cow disease and sporadic CJD are not connected.

39
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:29,000
They're suggesting that there may be a connection between BSE and sporadic CJD.

40
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:37,000
So if you tie all those things together, you've got a potentially much larger number of CJD patients in the United States.

41
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:41,000
You've got a potential linkage between BSE and sporadic CJD.

42
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:49,000
And then you've got this large number that are buried in this Alzheimer's disease epidemic in the United States.

43
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:56,000
Then I think this sort of aura of complacency in the United States that has happened

44
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:02,000
since the first case of mad cow disease was announced in Washington a year ago may be unwarranted.

45
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
This sense of complacency may be unwarranted.

46
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Talk a bit about why our system wouldn't discover people having CJD.

47
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:21,000
The real definitive way of discovering whether somebody has CJD, unfortunately, is waiting for them to die,

48
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:28,000
doing an autopsy on their brain, and looking at the pathology of the disease under the microscope.

49
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:37,000
A recent survey of pathologists in California came out just in the last six weeks

50
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:47,000
showed that over 70% of pathologists in California have a strong aversion to doing any autopsies on CJD patients.

51
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:49,000
And why is that?

52
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:56,000
Because the infectious organisms associated with, or infectious entities, prions associated with CJD

53
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:04,000
are not destroyed by the usual sterilization methods that are used to treat surgical instruments.

54
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:11,000
So it has already been shown that surgical instruments will transmit the disease to other people,

55
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:16,000
and other people have died because contaminated surgical instruments have been used.

56
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:25,000
70% of the pathologists in California do not want to contaminate their surgical instruments or their facilities with CJD.

57
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:36,000
So that is one reason why there has not been a rush to increase the numbers of autopsies

58
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:40,000
in order to define the number of CJD patients.

59
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:45,000
At the state level, the disease is not mandatory reportable.

60
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:57,000
So if a CJD patient is discovered in a rural locale outside the university research hospital system,

61
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:05,000
chances that a primary physician will diagnose CJD versus dementia, versus Alzheimer's disease,

62
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:11,000
is fairly low because CJD has not had a lot of press, medical press or media press.

63
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:20,000
So there's a tendency to lump these initial diagnoses into sort of a catch-all that includes dementia and Alzheimer's disease.

64
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:26,000
So therefore, a lot of these CJD cases would be dropping through the cracks.

65
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:37,000
Now the other issue is in the United Kingdom and in Europe, mad cow disease had a dramatic effect

66
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:44,000
right across the board, both on the health of people as well as on the economics of the beef industry over there.

67
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:52,000
The people in the United States have looked across the Atlantic and have seen the devastation that has happened across the Atlantic.

68
00:07:52,000 --> 00:08:00,000
And I would wager that there's many, many people at the CDC and the USDA who do not want to see a repeat

69
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:11,000
of what happened over in the United Kingdom and in Europe with over a million cows slaughtered to prevent spread of mad cow disease,

70
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:20,000
150 young people, teenagers in their 20s and counting dead from a human variant of mad cow disease.

71
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:28,000
So I think there's a strong kind of selection in the health authorities and in the agricultural authorities

72
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:33,000
to try to downplay the seriousness of these diseases.

73
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:38,000
I think the American population tends to look at these as specifically a European problem.

74
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:41,000
It has nothing to do with what's going on in the United States.

75
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:48,000
And my book, you know, another motivation for my book is to argue that that is not the case.

76
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:57,000
Well, I think one can understand how the USDA, which is more a front organization for the beef industry,

77
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:03,000
would not be so concerned with repeating what happened in the UK.

78
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:09,000
But you'd expect the CDC, which you have the impression that it's concerned with the health

79
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:15,000
and well-being of the citizens of this country, to be a little more on the ball on this.

80
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
Yeah, that's a very good point.

81
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:25,000
I think there's a strong drive at the CDC to downplay alarming the public,

82
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:30,000
unless there's data there that are actually beating you over the head.

83
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:36,000
And if you look at the experience of what happened in the United Kingdom,

84
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,000
I think you can really draw some very useful lessons.

85
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:47,000
And, you know, in my book, there's a very famous photograph of the agriculture minister,

86
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:53,000
John Gummer and his daughter Cordelia, posing in front of the cameras eating hamburgers.

87
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:58,000
And the purpose of that was to assure the British public that eating beef was safe.

88
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:03,000
And then within a short period of time, the first teenagers started dying of human mad cow disease.

89
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:06,000
Young people in their 20s started dying of human mad cow disease.

90
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:10,000
That was the kind of the attitude in the ministries,

91
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:15,000
both the health ministries and the agriculture ministries over in Britain, is do not alarm the public.

92
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:25,000
Let's continue along this line until we see everything is, you know, all the data are in, so to speak.

93
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:30,000
But in the meantime, you know, there were people dying of mad cow disease.

94
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:34,000
Over in the United States, even in the last nine months,

95
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:41,000
there have been a couple of worrying clusters of sporadic CJD in New York State.

96
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:50,000
It was announced in the last eight weeks that there was about five people had died in a small area in Ulster County in New York State.

97
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:54,000
The Catskills had died in the last few months from sporadic CJD.

98
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:57,000
Nine months ago in New Jersey, the state of New Jersey,

99
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:02,000
there were reports of about 15 people who had died over a period of time.

100
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:09,000
And all of those people had eaten at a single restaurant at a racetrack in New Jersey.

101
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:16,000
The CDC was tasked to go into both of these and to investigate.

102
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:20,000
Immediately, what they said was that these cases were sporadic CJD.

103
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
They had nothing whatever to do with mad cow disease.

104
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
They had nothing whatever to do with eating meat.

105
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:29,000
And therefore, they probably were statistical blips.

106
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:36,000
In other words, the number that's usually thrown out is that sporadic CJD is one in a million.

107
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:44,000
So here we have 15 people in New Jersey dying over a couple of years, which is a statistical aberration, to put it mildly.

108
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:49,000
CDC said it had nothing to do with eating tainted meat.

109
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:52,000
Therefore, they weren't going to fully investigate it.

110
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:54,000
It was kind of like a chicken and egg situation.

111
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:56,000
It has nothing to do with eating tainted meat.

112
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:57,000
Therefore, it's not a problem.

113
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,000
Therefore, we're not going to fully investigate it.

114
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:04,000
We're not going to go into these premises and check for prion contamination, that kind of thing.

115
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Now, interestingly, the data in the science journals started to contradict that a couple of years ago.

116
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:17,000
And all of this research is coming out of London and Europe,

117
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:24,000
where the research into prion diseases for obvious reasons is a lot more sophisticated than it is over here.

118
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:35,000
What they found over in the United Kingdom is that BSE may cause different forms of CJD in humans,

119
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:44,000
not only the so-called variant CJD, which has been unambiguously tied with tainted meat, but also perhaps sporadic CJD.

120
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:51,000
So there's research in the science journals, and the latest research came out less than a week ago,

121
00:12:52,000 --> 00:13:00,000
documenting exactly the same thing, that BSE may give rise to different forms of CJD in humans,

122
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:08,000
and that we may be missing the boat only by focusing on the so-called variant CJD, the human mad cow disease.

123
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:11,000
There may be other forms of CJD that BSE gives rise to.

124
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:24,000
So when the CDC confidently announces that sporadic CJD has nothing whatever to do with eating tainted beef,

125
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:30,000
the science is beginning to say otherwise. The science is trending in the opposite direction.

126
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:36,000
So I think one of the reasons that the CDC can get away with saying the one in a million number,

127
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:42,000
in addition to the fact that, as you pointed out earlier, the current climate is not to go in and test people

128
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:50,000
after they die to see if they have this disease, is that in this country there hasn't been a lot of coverage

129
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:58,000
of the vast history of the different parallel diseases that are similar to BSE.

130
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:03,000
I'm wondering if we can go into some of the details on that, fill people in.

131
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:13,000
My understanding is it actually starts in a couple of places. One is the sheep in the UK that we're getting.

132
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:14,000
Is it Scrapey?

133
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:15,000
Scrapey, yeah, that's right.

134
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:19,000
And then also, tell us about Papua New Guinea.

135
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:30,000
Yeah, the disease actually, the oldest known variant, if you want to call it, of these so-called prion diseases are sheep.

136
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:39,000
And it's been known that sheep have dropped from these neurological symptoms for a couple of centuries in the United Kingdom.

137
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:45,000
So it goes way, way back. But the really, I think from the United States perspective,

138
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:53,000
the really interesting events occurred in Papua New Guinea in the late 1950s

139
00:14:53,000 --> 00:15:03,000
when a scientist, Carlton Gajusek, who was funded by the Walter Reed Army Hospital

140
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:11,000
and Dr. Joe Smaddell, who was kind of like a kingpin at the NIH in Washington,

141
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:19,000
arrived over in Papua New Guinea in 1957 and began researching a mysterious brain disease that was killing

142
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:26,000
hundreds and eventually killed thousands of Foray tribespeople in the highlands in New Guinea.

143
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:30,000
They were dying of this mysterious brain disease.

144
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:38,000
The local tribespeople ascribed it to sorcery, and Gajusek was a brilliant physician.

145
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:45,000
I mean, he was one of these extraordinary people who could go into a country,

146
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:53,000
basically live in the wild with different tribespeople, sleep in flea-infested huts for months on end,

147
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:01,000
take enormous amounts of blood samples, do autopsies at 2 a.m. in the middle of a rainstorm, this kind of thing.

148
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:08,000
I mean, he was an extraordinary guy in terms of his ability to do this kind of medical research.

149
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:16,000
So what he began to do as a way of researching this was to autopsy several of these Foray people

150
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:18,000
who had died from this mysterious disease.

151
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:23,000
And by the way, these Foray people were cannibals, and the way they were spreading this disease,

152
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:27,000
it was found out later, was that they were eating their dead relatives after death.

153
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:33,000
So they would eat brain material, they would eat the rest of the corpse,

154
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:40,000
and that way the people who ingested it were getting the infectious entities, and they were dying.

155
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:43,000
And then when they died, they would spread it to their relatives.

156
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:49,000
So over a period of several decades, over 3,000 people died in that community.

157
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:55,000
So Gajusek, in his brilliant, inimitable way, began doing autopsies on these people,

158
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:00,000
persuaded them to do autopsies because it took a lot of persuasion,

159
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:04,000
because they didn't like their relatives being cut open and their brains being removed.

160
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:14,000
And he shipped a series of these brains back to the facilities at Bethesda and Fort Detrick, but mostly Bethesda.

161
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:23,000
What they started doing for a variety of reasons is they began to test whether or not this brain disease was transmissible.

162
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:34,000
So they found an isolated wildlife refuge at Patuxent, Maryland, between Washington and Baltimore, I believe it is.

163
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:41,000
And they got a bunch of chimpanzees, a whole bunch of different primates, and a whole bunch of different species of animals,

164
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:47,000
and they ground up the brains from these dead cannibals, made a brain slurry of them,

165
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:57,000
injected them into chimpanzees and primates and a whole variety of different species to see if these diseases were transmissible and they were.

166
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:03,000
The chimps came down with the brain disease and they died.

167
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:10,000
But this was in the middle of a wildlife refuge in Patuxent, Maryland.

168
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:17,000
The USDA actually in 1963 visited the facility and they were so appalled at the containment,

169
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:24,000
the restrictions and whether or not the animals could escape, they tried to shut the place down.

170
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:26,000
It was that bad.

171
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:37,000
So one of the theories in my book is that this kind of intense series of inoculations that had happened over a multiple year period in the 60s

172
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:42,000
may have contributed to spreading these prion diseases into the wildlife.

173
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:48,000
Because nothing was known in those days that prions could jump species.

174
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:59,000
The dramatic jump from cattle to humans that happened in the United Kingdom in the 90s was a very good example of how prions can jump species.

175
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:06,000
The way I would look at that whole thing is that it was like throwing gasoline on a fire.

176
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:10,000
There may have been low levels of prions.

177
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:18,000
For example, sheep were imported from the United Kingdom in 1947 into the United States that had scrapie.

178
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:26,000
So there may have been low levels of prion in sheep in the United States and maybe even mink.

179
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:35,000
But this kind of massive parallel inoculation series of experiments that happened out in Maryland in the 1960s,

180
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:41,000
my theory is that this could have spread to wildlife.

181
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:52,000
Now the other part of this thing is about 20 years after this whole episode of injection into wildlife,

182
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:58,000
there was a mysterious outbreak in 1985 in Stetsonville, Wisconsin,

183
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:07,000
where 4,000 mink died of a strange, and these were farm mink, they died of a strange brain disease.

184
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:15,000
A University of Wisconsin research veterinarian called Dr. Richard Marsh went up there to investigate.

185
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:19,000
What he did was he took the brains from these mink and examined them.

186
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:24,000
And he found that all of those mink had died of essentially mad mink disease.

187
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:28,000
They had died from the brain disease.

188
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:33,000
So he investigated how these animals might have got this disease.

189
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:37,000
He looked at their feeding habits, he looked at what they had been fed,

190
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:42,000
and it happened that the owner of the mink ranch had kept extremely meticulous records.

191
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:47,000
And it turned out that this rancher had been feeding the mink dead cows.

192
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:50,000
Ground up remains of dead cows.

193
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:56,000
So this was 1985, this was not 2003, this was 1985.

194
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:02,000
So the strong implication from Dr. Richard Marsh's investigations,

195
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:04,000
and he published all this stuff in science journals,

196
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:12,000
was that there was a mad cow disease variant present in beef that had been fed to mink

197
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:15,000
and had caused the mink to die of mad mink disease.

198
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:22,000
So the idea that mad cow disease has only been discovered in one single animal

199
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:27,000
in Washington state in 2003 is not exactly the truth,

200
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:34,000
because there is strong evidence that this disease has been around in this country for decades.

201
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:42,000
And so while all this is happening, I understand there was also independent efforts

202
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:45,000
by different scientists kind of working this at different angles,

203
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:51,000
looking at the transmissibility of the disease between, let's say,

204
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:59,000
mice they were testing and hamsters and the cows and seeing which directions the disease could go.

205
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:04,000
