00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:35,000
Talk about a little bit about because we're talking about different technically have been labeled different diseases.

301
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:41,000
Let's say Scrapey, BSE, CJD, but they all share something in common.

302
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:45,000
They're all exactly the same mechanism of disease.

303
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:49,000
And that is this mysterious infectious entity called the prion.

304
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:53,000
Now, a prion is not a virus. It's not a bacterium.

305
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:56,000
It is a protein that everybody has.

306
00:32:56,000 --> 00:33:01,000
But the difference is that protein changes shape into a new lethal form.

307
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:12,000
And that the change once it changes shape, it's almost like a different structure of a protein that that creates a lethal form of this protein.

308
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:23,000
The normal form is supposedly protective in the cell, but the lethal form is is associated with widespread cell death.

309
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:35,000
So if you eat a hamburger that's tainted with prions, it goes first into the gut and then it moves into the gut associated lymphoid tissue,

310
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:44,000
which is called GALT, which is a dense area of lymph lymphatic tissue around the gut.

311
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:50,000
It then moves into the lymph system and then moves into the peripheral nervous system and eventually central nervous system,

312
00:33:51,000 --> 00:34:00,000
which is the spinal cord and brain. But it does it is known to migrate through the through the lymphoid tissue.

313
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:15,000
The prion is definitely one of the most mysterious things known in infectious disease because it breaks every single rule that's been known in science in the last 50 years.

314
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:22,000
It doesn't carry DNA, doesn't carry RNA, which are the two things that viruses and bacteria use to replicate.

315
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:31,000
These prions seem to be able to force normal prions to adopt the lethal shape.

316
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:39,000
And so it's kind of like a chain reaction in the cell and in the cells next to those cells where it's over many,

317
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:49,000
many years these hundreds of millions of cells and then billions of brain cells die from this slow transmission like a chain reaction in the brain.

318
00:34:49,000 --> 00:35:00,000
And it's only when the terminal stages of this whole process, which can take years if not decades, that the person begins to notice symptoms.

319
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:17,000
The person begins to notice forgetfulness, mood changes, feeling really, really weird and feeling off, shaking, start trembling, muscle spasms and then seizures.

320
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:26,000
And then it really starts getting serious where all memory begins to go, person doesn't recognize family members.

321
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:34,000
This all happens right after the first initial symptoms and it may take months, sometimes maybe a year or two to die.

322
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:44,000
Now, the very initial symptoms of this, of CJD, are there's some overlap with the very initial symptoms of Alzheimer's.

323
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:50,000
The difference with CJD and Alzheimer's is Alzheimer's takes much, much longer to progress.

324
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:57,000
People can last for years if not maybe even a decade between the initial symptoms and final terminal stages.

325
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:03,000
With CJD, it is usually months, sometimes maybe 18 months kind of thing.

326
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:13,000
But the prion has already been the subject of two Nobel Prizes that have been won,

327
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:22,000
first by Carlton Gajuszek for the discovery of the infectiousness in the kuru population in New Guinea,

328
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:30,000
and then the second one by Dr. Stanley Prusner from the University of California in San Francisco for his actual discovery of the prions.

329
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:37,000
And, you know, the still scientists around, even in 2004, who were saying that prions cannot possibly exist,

330
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:47,000
it's like a bad science fiction movie, you know, that these entities, they don't even require DNA, RNA to replicate.

331
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:51,000
They infect other people, they jump species, they're indestructible.

