395
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:49,000
you know, going back to Dr. Richard Marsh's 1985 discoveries and all the way to now on the wildlife,

396
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:55,000
they really shake their heads at the lack of attention that's being focused on this whole thing.

397
00:44:56,000 --> 00:45:03,000
And then on top of everything else is this epidemic in deer and elk that's spreading through the country, brain waste and diseases.

398
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:07,000
And they're all the same thing. They're all prion based diseases.

399
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:19,000
You know, they're suggesting that the United States may be able to learn from the mistakes that were made in the United Kingdom and in Europe.

400
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:24,000
But, you know, I think history has a habit of repeating itself endlessly.

401
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:35,000
And, you know, there's a photograph in my book right beside that British agriculture minister and his daughter eating hamburgers.

402
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:41,000
There's a photograph in my book of the then Prime Minister of Canada, Jean Chrétien.

403
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:48,000
He's two days after the announcement in May 2003 of the first mad cow in Canada.

404
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:57,000
Prime Minister Jean Chrétien sat down in a restaurant in Ottawa and in front of the cameras put a whole bunch of beef into his mouth and started eating beef.

405
00:45:57,000 --> 00:46:04,000
Again, the message was exactly the same as the minister and his daughter in Britain that eating beef was perfectly safe.

406
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:09,000
There's nothing to worry about. Canadians should continue eating beef. You know, everything is okay.

407
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:14,000
Same thing happened in the United States right after the mad cow case in Washington.

408
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:27,000
There was a relentless, you know, overdrive of publicity and public relations for about two to three months right after that announcement.

409
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:40,000
And, you know, Secretary Anne Veneman retired just in the last few days, and she has been praised and credited with keeping American confidence in beef,

410
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:44,000
consumers' confidence in beef at an all-time high.

411
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:54,000
Just a mere three months after the announcement in Washington of this mad cow case, CNN ran a story entitled Cow Brain Sandwiches.

412
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:02,000
And there was a, I'm not sure if it was in Georgia or somewhere in the southeastern part of the United States,

413
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:11,000
but there was a story about this group of people, families, down in this area who were still eating cow brain sandwiches, which is apparently a local delicacy.

414
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:16,000
This was a mere three months after the first documented case of mad cow disease.

415
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:23,000
Now, you know, eating cow brain sandwiches is, I would consider, a fairly high-risk procedure,

416
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:30,000
but it was a measure of the success of the public relations exercise that the USDA had successfully completed

417
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:39,000
that people, the American consumers, were happily continuing to eat, you know, beef, including cow brain sandwiches.

418
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:44,000
My understanding as well, jumping back to the amount of cattle being tested here in the U.S.,

419
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:50,000
in addition to it being a microscopic number of the actual herd of 35 million being tested,

420
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:57,000
that they're only focusing on the downer cows, and because I talked to Dave Luther earlier in this year,

421
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:05,000
if we look at the single cow that turned up as being the first recognized case of BSC in the U.S., that was not a downer cow.

422
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:12,000
So they're ignoring, you know, the very portion of the herd, the bulk of the herd that turned out as positive.

423
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:21,000
Yes, I think Dave Lothan did the country a tremendous service by coming forward and explaining how exactly that whole thing went down.

424
00:48:22,000 --> 00:48:27,000
The implications, I think, of what Dave Lothan was saying are really staggering,

425
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:36,000
because what they're saying is that the program, the USDA program that was focused on testing only downer cows,

426
00:48:36,000 --> 00:48:43,000
which are cows that drop for any number of reasons and can't walk anymore,

427
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:51,000
is that the cow that was found in Washington State was not a downer cow, it was actually walking, it was quite capable of standing up.

428
00:48:51,000 --> 00:48:58,000
That means that the program that the USDA was focusing on just downer cows was missing the boat,

429
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:01,000
and that that cow was found completely by accident.

430
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:13,000
I understand that there's still an ongoing investigation at the federal level into falsifying the records out there in Washington State

431
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:17,000
regarding whether that animal was a downer or a walker.

432
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:22,000
And, you know, that's winding its way through the bureaucratic channels right now.

433
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:33,000
But there's sufficient concern about that whole thing that the idea that the cow, the single cow that has been admitted to,

434
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:40,000
was actually walking rather than downing, a downer, is staggering.

435
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:48,000
Because it means that how many other cows have been missed if the USDA is only focusing on downer cows.

436
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:58,000
And, you know, that raises a whole series of questions about symptoms, how long it takes for symptoms to appear in cattle.

437
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:03,000
Is it only at this much-talked-about 30-month period?

438
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:10,000
30-month is supposedly the break-off period where cows begin to develop symptoms of mad cow disease.

439
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:20,000
The saying goes that there's no point in testing pre-30-month, but only post-30-month.

440
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:25,000
So you've got a higher probability of detecting mad cow disease in the older animals, which is true.

441
00:50:25,000 --> 00:50:32,000
But does that mean that any animals that are less than 30 months of age do not have prion disease?

442
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:44,000
Again, there's a whole slew of convoluted logic that is really self-defeating in this whole thing.

443
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:53,000
I think Dave Lutheran really put his finger on the whole thing by coming forward like that and saying that the animal that he killed was not a downer cow.

444
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:58,000
And I think the implications are still reverberating through the country.

445
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:06,000
But by and large, in terms of the media, that particular part was not picked up on the way it should have been,

446
00:51:06,000 --> 00:51:13,000
because it really exposed a sort of a flank in the whole testing process in this country that, you know,

447
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:18,000
I think people are really going through the motions of testing rather than, you know,

448
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:26,000
genuinely going after to see what kind of the baseline is in the United States with regard to numbers of mad cows.

449
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:35,000
And finally, quickly, the media has repeated what has come out of Anne Veneman and the USDA,

450
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:43,000
saying that if you just take out, for instance, the brains and the spinal cord and maybe a couple other organs,

451
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:50,000
that, you know, you'll be relatively safe, that the beef will be clean. What's the truth to that?

452
00:51:50,000 --> 00:51:58,000
Well, you know, that's another of these issues that needs to be intensively researched.

453
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:03,000
If you look at the New England Journal of Medicine recently came out in the last year,

454
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:09,000
came out with an article showing that CJD humans had lots of prions in their muscle.

455
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:14,000
They had detectable, I should say, rather than lots, detectable prions in their muscle.

456
00:52:14,000 --> 00:52:19,000
Sheep, scrapie-infected sheep, have prions detectable in their muscle.

457
00:52:19,000 --> 00:52:23,000
Hamsters have detectable prions in their muscle.

458
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:29,000
What the USDA has been saying is that there have never been prions found in cow muscle.

459
00:52:29,000 --> 00:52:35,000
And, you know, there have been a couple of studies published so far, but the numbers are so low

460
00:52:35,000 --> 00:52:41,000
that there really needs to be a large increase in the resources devoted to testing.

461
00:52:41,000 --> 00:52:48,000
Asking that simple question, you know, do we really need to increase the sensitivity of the tests

462
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:54,000
in order to be able to detect these prion proteins in cow muscle?

463
00:52:54,000 --> 00:53:00,000
Because if prions are detected in cow muscle, that means that the entire beef supply,

464
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:05,000
which is, you know, steaks that people eat, again, is at risk.

465
00:53:05,000 --> 00:53:12,000
You know, muscle is full of nerves, it's full of blood vessels.

466
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:19,000
It's already known through, again, research from the United Kingdom that prions are transmitted in blood.

467
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:27,000
Both the blood donors and acceptors of blood transfusions in the United Kingdom have died of CJD.

468
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:34,000
And in France, they're currently tracking a donor who has died of CJD,

469
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:37,000
who has donated blood to multiple different people.

470
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:40,000
So, you know, it's known that the blood carries prions, too.

471
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:49,000
So the idea that beef, which is infused with both nerves and with blood vessels, would be entirely free of prions.

472
00:53:49,000 --> 00:53:57,000
Again, you know, if you look at the science and you look at the public relations, I think there's a definite gap.

473
00:53:57,000 --> 00:54:02,000
All right. What final thoughts would you like to share with our listeners?

474
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:13,000
Well, I think the real essence of this book is really, if you will, a wake-up call to the people in this country,

475
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:20,000
that there have been a tremendous amount of experiences that have happened across the water.

476
00:54:20,000 --> 00:54:27,000
The United Kingdom in the last few years have put up thousands and thousands of pages of documents on their website,

477
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:35,000
the BSE Inquiry website, which people can go to to look to see what the mistakes, the bureaucratic mistakes,

478
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:40,000
there were so many and they were so varied.

479
00:54:40,000 --> 00:54:44,000
The United States has a tremendous amount of lessons to learn.

480
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:51,000
I believe that the complacency that exists in the United States regarding mad cow disease,

481
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:58,000
regarding prion diseases, both in the wildlife and in the beef and dairy supply.

482
00:54:58,000 --> 00:55:02,000
I think that that sense of complacency is misplaced.

483
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:12,000
I believe that we really need to get a whole program, series of programs of testing urgently in this country.

484
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:15,000
All right. Well, I want to thank you for spending time with us today.

485
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:18,000
You're very welcome. It was really good to talk to you.

486
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:21,000
We have just been talking with Colm Keller.

487
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:29,000
He is the author of Brain Trust, the hidden connection between mad cow and misdiagnosed Alzheimer's disease.

